title: Want To Buy:  Buyer Beware
postcontent:
It was suggested by a regular user of this board, that I post my experience today with a ammo purchase.
This gentlemen, Mr. Tackett, responded to an ad I posted seeking 22 ammo. He advised he had 1350 of ammo, from three different manufacturers, in bulk, other than two 100 round boxes of CCI ammo.
He stated a price, I countered with a different price, he countered with a price delivered to a place along I-70. I declined the offer.
He then emailed me back with a slightly lower price, delivered to the point along I-70. I responded advising I would take the ammo, and a meet time was agreed upon.
Then just hours before the agreed time, he emailed me and backed out of the per-arrangement stating his concern for gas prices and snow flurries.(he drives a SUV)
He then lowered the price a little on the condition that I drive to Columbus to meet him near his home. Once again, I agreed to his terms, and met him on the out skirts of Columbus.
After the deal was done and I returned home I decided to count all the bulk ammo, and to no great surprise found the actual quantities less than what he stated, by 125 rounds.
I informed him of the error which he promptly replied that his son had done the counting, and suggesting the error was not his responsibility. He of course said he would make it good, but of course, the 125 rounds was not worth another drive to Columbus.

Long story short, I would suggest extreme caution to anyone thinking of dealing with this guy, especially when it comes to bulk ammo.

He refuses to give you his phone number, but his email info is:
He uses a name of Mr. Tackett
Email address is REDACTED
Says all emails come from his smart phone which is a galaxy S III

title: For Sale:  Gonzales 'Come And Take It' Flags
postcontent:
In late September, 1835, Colonel Ugartechea, the commander of the Mexican garrison at San Antonio, sent a few men to Gonzales to recover a cannon that had been loaned to the town to fight off occasional Indian attacks. The citizens of Gonzales realized that the intent of the move was to disarm possible rebels, and so the request was denied.

Ugartechea then sent dragoons under Captain Francisco Castaneda to demand the cannon unconditionally. As word of the conflict spread, the Texan force grew to over 200 armed men and the town was fortified. The cannon was mounted on a wagon, and blacksmiths hammered iron scrap and chains inth the cannonballs.

Two ladies of the town, Cynthia Burns and Evaline DeWitt, painted a flag on cotton cloth, depicting the cannon, the lone star of Texas and a clear challenge to the enemy.

The Mexican troops moved north to ford the river and approach Gonzales. The Texans decided that they had to attack before Mexican reinforcements arrived. They crossed the river at dusk, formed their battle lines at night and surprised the Mexicans at dawn on October 2nd.

The battle that followed was brief; when the Texans opened fire, the Mexicans withdrew, abandoning their supplies. Stephen F. Austin joined the army as commander on October 10th, and the other Texans, under the command of James Collingsworth, took the Goliad the next day. On October 12th, the march on San Antonio began.

3'x5' Gonzales flags available at www.2Adefender.com, only $8.59.

location: Shelby, NC, North Carolina, United States
postcontent: Swedish Mausers are a family of bolt-action rifles based on an improved variant of Mauser's earlier Model 1893, but using the 6.5x55 cartridge and incorporating unique design elements, as requested by Sweden. In 1898, production at Carl Gustaf's stads Gevarsfaktori in Eskilstuna in Sweden. All Swedish Mausers were chambered for the 6.5x55mm cartridge and all Swedish-made actions were proof tested with a single cartridge developing 66,000psi. Swedish Mausers were manufactured by Waffenfabrik Muser Oberndorf a/n in Germany or in Sweden by Carl Gustafs stads Gevarsfaktori and Husqvarna Vaspenfabriks Aktiebolag. All Swedish Mausers, whether built in Germany or Sweden, were fabricated using a Swedish-supplied high grade tool steel alloyed with nickel, copper and vanadium, a product noted for its strength and corrosion resistance.

title: For Sale:  SA 1953 M1 Garand 4.2mil s/n
postcontent:
1953 Springfield Armory M1 Garand 42379XX serial number collector grade condition.  An excellent specimen from the start of the Korean war production.

Metal finish is approximately 98% and original based on the bright chamber and crispness of the machining marks throughout.  Wear patterns on the moving parts shows very little evidence of use.  CMP paperwork shows purchase as a collector grade in 1999.

Barrel is marked with SA drawing number 2 53 date the heat lot and P with punch.  Trigger housing, hammer, bolt and op rod are all SA marked with the correct post war drawing numbers.  The safety is marked with a U but matches the wear patterns of the other pieces.  The TE105 rear sight has a DRC marked windage knob and a NHC marked elevation knob.  High hump gas lock with NHC marked lock screw.

The stock has a nice JLG cartouche with small ordnance wheel and circled P with serifs on the pistol grip.  The stock has some handling damage but is in overall very good condition.  The colors on the handguards and stock match quite nicely.

Korean War production started in late 1952 with serial number 4.2 million.  This is one of the first 40,000 rifles made during the second production period.  Most rifles of this vintage would have seen plenty of use and abuse in Asia.  It is very uncommon to find an early post WWII rifles in this pristine condition.  $1800

title: For Sale:  1942 SA M1 Garand 0.9 million serial number
postcontent:
1942 Springfield Armory M1 Garand 905,0XX serial number in very good unrestored condition.  The stock has been refinished by a previous owner.

Metal finish is approximately 90% and original based on the bright chamber and crispness of the machining marks throughout. All of the moving parts shows similar wear patterns indicating these parts have lived together for a while and have not been changed around anytime recently.

The barrel has the correct upside down S-A-10-42 marking and P with punch mark.  The narrow base front sight still has the lead seal on the sight screw.  All revision numbers are correct for late 1942 production; -3 curve sided op rod (uncut), -8 trigger housing, -3 hammer, -9 safety, -11 follower, short fork riveted follower rod, round nose clip latch, grooved lower HG clip. The short pinion rear sight has a checkered elevation cap and knurled windage cap with flush nut.  Both with closed arrows per SA manufacture. Of special note is that many of the small parts were left unfinished.  The gas screw, firing pin, ejector, hammer spring guide, sear, follower slide, bullet guide and accelerator are all in the white.

The previous owner purchased this rifle in its current condition in the 1970's with the glossy refinished stock.  Unfortunately all cartouches were removed, only a partial remnant of the circled P with serifs remains on the pistol grip.  However the stock is an early WW2 stock with scooped latch cutout, long chanel front and stamped type stock ferrule with small hole.  The stock has not been sanded excessively as there is no proud metal anywhere.

While this rifle is a bit late in 1942 for a flush nut sight, however it is well documented that a SA used leftover parts as needed during 1942 and 1943.  A number of known original rifles have been documented with earlier type sights during the mid war period. I believe this sight is original to this rifle.  

The long channel stock is also out of sequence and I believe has been exchanged from an earlier rifle.

A very good quality early WW2 rifle.
